WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000 line:15% 
(piano music)

2
00:00:06.827 --> 00:00:09.108
<v ->If you were to look at one single factor</v>

3
00:00:09.108 --> 00:00:11.987
that creates more fear than any other on a global scale

4
00:00:11.987 --> 00:00:13.867
it would certainly be money.

5
00:00:13.867 --> 00:00:15.567
So it's no surprise that most of us

6
00:00:15.567 --> 00:00:18.967
have varying degrees of unhealthy relationships with money.

7
00:00:18.967 --> 00:00:20.747
Either fear of not having enough

8
00:00:20.747 --> 00:00:22.847
or losing what we have.

9
00:00:22.847 --> 00:00:24.967
Karen McCall was in dire straits

10
00:00:24.967 --> 00:00:27.508
when she was forced to deal with her money demons.

11
00:00:27.508 --> 00:00:30.988
It turned into a deep spiritual process of self evaluation

12
00:00:30.988 --> 00:00:33.347
that was in turn the start of a career

13
00:00:33.347 --> 00:00:35.388
in helping others to shine the light

14
00:00:35.388 --> 00:00:36.928
on their own money bogey man.

15
00:00:36.928 --> 00:00:40.127
All of which she shares in her book Financial Recovery.

16
00:00:40.127 --> 00:00:42.794
<v  Voiceover>Karen, I'm so happy to be talking</v>

17
00:00:42.794 --> 00:00:43.813
to you about this

18
00:00:43.813 --> 00:00:45.653
because many of the people watching right now

19
00:00:45.653 --> 00:00:49.733
probably have an unhealthy relationship with money.

20
00:00:49.733 --> 00:00:54.093
Whether it's under earning, just denying that we're in debt,

21
00:00:54.093 --> 00:00:55.043
not wanting to look at

22
00:00:55.043 --> 00:00:57.303
because we can't figure our way out of it,

23
00:00:57.303 --> 00:00:59.103
or not saving.

24
00:00:59.103 --> 00:01:00.903
It seems the most people have some kind of

25
00:01:00.903 --> 00:01:02.543
dysfunction around this,

26
00:01:02.543 --> 00:01:05.303
and these times have been challenging for people

27
00:01:05.303 --> 00:01:06.823
with the loss of work,

28
00:01:06.823 --> 00:01:08.183
but you were challenged.

29
00:01:08.183 --> 00:01:10.223
You weren't always this together.

30
00:01:10.223 --> 00:01:11.263
<v ->Right.</v>

31
00:01:11.263 --> 00:01:13.083
<v Voiceover>Take you back a couple decades</v>

32
00:01:13.083 --> 00:01:14.463
and you were very un-together.

33
00:01:14.463 --> 00:01:16.443
Let's talk about how traumatic your relationship

34
00:01:16.443 --> 00:01:19.283
with money was that really launched you on this path.

35
00:01:19.283 --> 00:01:22.003
<v ->Regina, if you would have known me 27 years ago,</v>

36
00:01:22.003 --> 00:01:23.943
what you would have seen

37
00:01:23.943 --> 00:01:25.863
was a successful looking business woman,

38
00:01:25.863 --> 00:01:27.463
hopping in a car every morning

39
00:01:27.463 --> 00:01:29.703
driving to San Francisco's financial district.

40
00:01:29.703 --> 00:01:31.903
Before I would board the elevator

41
00:01:31.903 --> 00:01:33.763
that would take me to the 31st floor.

42
00:01:33.763 --> 00:01:36.883
I'd stop and get my latte and my big bran muffin,

43
00:01:36.883 --> 00:01:38.760
and if you would have seen me,

44
00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:40.900
you would have thought, "Wow, what a success."

45
00:01:40.900 --> 00:01:42.380
You know, this corner office with a view

46
00:01:42.380 --> 00:01:44.780
of the fantastic San Francisco Bay.

47
00:01:44.780 --> 00:01:46.440
However, I had a big secret.

48
00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:48.100
And that secret was that at home

49
00:01:48.100 --> 00:01:49.820
on top of my refrigerator

50
00:01:49.820 --> 00:01:51.660
I had this big bowl of bills,

51
00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:53.260
unopened bills,

52
00:01:53.260 --> 00:01:55.400
and several from the IRS.

53
00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:59.080
It was just the most painful time in my life.

54
00:01:59.080 --> 00:02:00.600
No one would have guessed that I was

55
00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:02.081
on the verge of financial ruin.

56
00:02:02.081 --> 00:02:03.380
<v Regina>Did you tell anyone?</v>

57
00:02:03.380 --> 00:02:04.820
Did you share this with anyone?

58
00:02:04.820 --> 00:02:06.720
<v ->I didn't, I was dating a guy at the time.</v>

59
00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:08.060
A man named Tom,

60
00:02:08.060 --> 00:02:09.601
and he suspected.

61
00:02:09.601 --> 00:02:11.100
He was too polite to ever bring it up,

62
00:02:11.100 --> 00:02:12.600
but he would show up at my house,

63
00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:16.000
at my apartment rather with these audio binders

64
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.060
of audio cassettes, self help audio cassettes.

65
00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:21.720
And I would just pile them up on my floor.

66
00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:24.960
But I never had a dime to contribute to

67
00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:26.581
even a cup of coffee that we had,

68
00:02:26.581 --> 00:02:28.600
and he definitely suspected there was a problem.

69
00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:30.580
<v Regina>And you were earning right?</v>

70
00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:31.400
<v ->I was earning money.</v>

71
00:02:31.400 --> 00:02:32.120
<v Regina>You were earning money,</v>

72
00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:33.152
but what were you doing with that money?

73
00:02:33.152 --> 00:02:34.372
<v ->Well this is the thing.</v>

74
00:02:34.372 --> 00:02:36.032
I had been married before.

75
00:02:36.032 --> 00:02:37.553
My kids were off to college,

76
00:02:37.553 --> 00:02:41.692
and so I had a fairly sizable amount of money,

77
00:02:41.692 --> 00:02:43.153
after my divorce.

78
00:02:43.153 --> 00:02:46.872
However, I was alone for the first time in my life.

79
00:02:46.872 --> 00:02:48.773
I had never learned about money,

80
00:02:48.773 --> 00:02:52.032
and I felt way too embarrassed and too ashamed

81
00:02:52.032 --> 00:02:54.232
to let anybody know that I didn't know.

82
00:02:54.232 --> 00:02:56.733
So I just watched my savings go down,

83
00:02:56.733 --> 00:02:58.412
and during the 80s you know,

84
00:02:58.412 --> 00:03:00.412
the earliest easy time to get credit.

85
00:03:00.412 --> 00:03:01.392
<v Regina>Yes, that's when it started.</v>

86
00:03:01.392 --> 00:03:02.792
<v ->So I got the credit cards,</v>

87
00:03:02.792 --> 00:03:05.412
and it was just, I was just in this money coma.

88
00:03:05.412 --> 00:03:09.280
Just unconscious of the reality of what was happening to me.

89
00:03:09.280 --> 00:03:11.521
And it wasn't until coming home one day,

90
00:03:11.521 --> 00:03:14.561
and there was an eviction notice on my door,

91
00:03:14.561 --> 00:03:17.918
and that was the time when I said,

92
00:03:17.918 --> 00:03:19.771
"I really have to bring down that bowl."

93
00:03:19.771 --> 00:03:21.550
And the good news is,

94
00:03:21.550 --> 00:03:24.390
I was drawn to that stack of audio cassettes

95
00:03:24.390 --> 00:03:26.390
and I pulled out one that said,

96
00:03:26.390 --> 00:03:29.070
"Possibility Thinking" by Dr. Robert Schuler,

97
00:03:29.070 --> 00:03:31.810
and as I listened to his soothing words,

98
00:03:31.810 --> 00:03:34.750
I mustered the courage to bring down that bowl.

99
00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:36.411
<v Regina>And open those bills?</v>

100
00:03:36.411 --> 00:03:37.910
<v ->Open all those bills.</v>

101
00:03:37.910 --> 00:03:39.530
Throw away all the duplicates.

102
00:03:39.530 --> 00:03:41.871
Made a list of everything I owed.

103
00:03:41.871 --> 00:03:43.530
<v Regina>I mean you had already gotten sobered</v>

104
00:03:43.530 --> 00:03:45.517
enough to do this, so to speak.

105
00:03:45.517 --> 00:03:48.437
However, were you shocked to see what you owed?

106
00:03:48.437 --> 00:03:51.577
<v ->You know, I was shocked to see what I owed,</v>

107
00:03:51.577 --> 00:03:52.937
but it was such a relief Regina,

108
00:03:52.937 --> 00:03:55.308
because not knowing,

109
00:03:55.308 --> 00:03:57.188
that not knowing and just worrying.

110
00:03:57.188 --> 00:04:00.908
Even though I was numbing myself in many different ways,

111
00:04:00.908 --> 00:04:02.808
and just not paying attention to it,

112
00:04:02.808 --> 00:04:05.148
it did impact my sleep,

113
00:04:05.148 --> 00:04:06.988
my sense of self-esteem.

114
00:04:06.988 --> 00:04:08.988
I couldn't breath.

115
00:04:08.988 --> 00:04:10.388
You know, I couldn't breath.

116
00:04:10.388 --> 00:04:13.888
It was just a very, very stressful, stressful time for me.

117
00:04:13.888 --> 00:04:16.548
<v Regina>Sure, and I think a lot of people</v>

118
00:04:16.548 --> 00:04:17.688
can relate to that.

119
00:04:17.688 --> 00:04:20.168
What was interesting is because at that time

120
00:04:20.168 --> 00:04:22.408
credit was becoming available, right?

121
00:04:22.408 --> 00:04:24.568
But we didn't understand the implications

122
00:04:24.568 --> 00:04:27.528
like we do in 2011

123
00:04:27.528 --> 00:04:30.648
of what it means to not be credit worthy.

124
00:04:30.648 --> 00:04:33.528
After you've gotten drunk on credit for 20, 30 years

125
00:04:33.528 --> 00:04:37.288
that's our savings, we don't even bother to save.

126
00:04:37.288 --> 00:04:38.848
Put it on the card.

127
00:04:38.848 --> 00:04:42.508
That's created a whole different psyche

128
00:04:42.508 --> 00:04:44.008
about this worthiness,

129
00:04:44.008 --> 00:04:45.608
"Oh my god, I'll lose my credit rating."

130
00:04:45.608 --> 00:04:47.148
And we'll get into that in a little bit

131
00:04:47.148 --> 00:04:50.009
because that's part of this kind of drunken debt cycle.

132
00:04:50.009 --> 00:04:51.908
That we've got sucked into.

133
00:04:51.908 --> 00:04:53.308
<v ->It's a really important concept.</v>

134
00:04:53.308 --> 00:04:54.929
I look forward to talking to you about that.

135
00:04:54.929 --> 00:04:57.268
<v Regina>Well I mean, we can go linear on this,</v>

136
00:04:57.268 --> 00:04:59.968
but let's make sure we get back to that.

137
00:04:59.968 --> 00:05:00.828
<v ->Okay.</v>

138
00:05:00.828 --> 00:05:03.649
<v Regina>Okay, so then you had gotten to a point,</v>

139
00:05:03.649 --> 00:05:05.948
I love this part in your book where,

140
00:05:05.948 --> 00:05:08.868
you had to choose between your car payment,

141
00:05:08.868 --> 00:05:11.068
you're a sales person so you had to have a car.

142
00:05:11.068 --> 00:05:12.068
<v ->Right.</v>

143
00:05:12.068 --> 00:05:14.348
<v Regina>And whether or not you could afford your rent.</v>

144
00:05:14.348 --> 00:05:15.888
And then tell us what happened from there.

145
00:05:15.888 --> 00:05:19.148
<v ->Okay, well that night, that I listed all the bills.</v>

146
00:05:19.148 --> 00:05:21.168
Two things became crystal clear.

147
00:05:21.168 --> 00:05:25.028
One was, I couldn't keep my car and my apartment,

148
00:05:25.028 --> 00:05:28.668
and the other thing was I had to come up with money quick.

149
00:05:28.668 --> 00:05:31.696
So I bought a San Francisco chronicle.

150
00:05:31.696 --> 00:05:33.796
I poured over the classifieds,

151
00:05:33.796 --> 00:05:36.796
and I found an ad "Professional Couple in Pacific Heights

152
00:05:36.796 --> 00:05:39.557
"Seeks Cook Five Nights a Week".

153
00:05:39.557 --> 00:05:41.936
And that afternoon, I was in their

154
00:05:41.936 --> 00:05:44.321
beautiful Pacific Heights Mansion

155
00:05:44.321 --> 00:05:47.460
interviewing to be their live in cook.

156
00:05:47.460 --> 00:05:49.080
It was a little confusing to them,

157
00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:50.500
but then again I made up a story

158
00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:53.020
about this is an opportunity for me to save and get ahead.

159
00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:55.001
<v Regina>Yeah, you looked a little bit over,</v>

160
00:05:55.001 --> 00:05:56.720
<v ->A little different than most people have.</v>

161
00:05:56.720 --> 00:05:58.200
<v Regina>Who are qualified as their cook.</v>

162
00:05:58.200 --> 00:06:01.560
<v ->Yes, yes, and I had this job in the financial district.</v>

163
00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:02.920
<v Regina>Did you know how to cook?</v>

164
00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:03.960
<v ->I did.</v>

165
00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:05.380
I did know how to cook, yes.

166
00:06:05.380 --> 00:06:10.380
The other thing, was I need to come up with money fast.

167
00:06:10.380 --> 00:06:12.821
So that next Saturday,

168
00:06:12.821 --> 00:06:16.060
I held a sale in the courtyard of my apartment building,

169
00:06:16.060 --> 00:06:17.760
and I sold everything I owned.

170
00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:20.400
You know, 40 years of precious possessions

171
00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:22.180
just gone in an afternoon.

172
00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:25.520
That night I moved into the maid's quarters

173
00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:28.120
of their home in Pacific Heights,

174
00:06:28.120 --> 00:06:29.660
and so you know,

175
00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:31.501
"Hey, headed to the financial district"

176
00:06:31.501 --> 00:06:32.760
and everything looked fine,

177
00:06:32.760 --> 00:06:34.161
but at the end of the day,

178
00:06:34.161 --> 00:06:36.880
I would come home, put on an apron,

179
00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:37.940
change out of my business suit,

180
00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:39.741
put on an apron and head to the kitchen.

181
00:06:39.741 --> 00:06:43.830
I will tell you, that, did I want that to be a secret,

182
00:06:43.830 --> 00:06:45.700
did I feel shame about that?

183
00:06:45.700 --> 00:06:46.740
<v Regina>Yes.</v>

184
00:06:46.740 --> 00:06:49.380
<v ->Even my daughters, I didn't tell the truth.</v>

185
00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:52.001
I just said, "Again, this is an opportunity for me

186
00:06:52.001 --> 00:06:53.380
"to save money, get ahead."

187
00:06:53.380 --> 00:06:56.280
No, I was in dire straits.

188
00:06:56.280 --> 00:06:59.841
<v Regina>And the low point must have been</v>

189
00:06:59.841 --> 00:07:01.400
missing your grandma's funeral.

190
00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:03.100
<v ->Oh my gosh.</v>

191
00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:05.401
That was when I wrote the book,

192
00:07:05.401 --> 00:07:09.740
probably one of the most painful times in my life.

193
00:07:09.740 --> 00:07:11.540
Remembering that story.

194
00:07:11.540 --> 00:07:14.101
That because my credit cards were maxed out,

195
00:07:14.101 --> 00:07:16.980
because I was ashamed to tell anyone,

196
00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:21.760
I was back at a training on the East Coast.

197
00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:24.420
I got the call that my grandmother had died.

198
00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:26.281
My grandma had been the dearest person

199
00:07:26.281 --> 00:07:27.440
in the world to me.

200
00:07:27.440 --> 00:07:28.401
<v Regina>You had a tough childhood?</v>

201
00:07:28.401 --> 00:07:30.480
<v ->I did, and my grandmother was so dear.</v>

202
00:07:30.480 --> 00:07:34.701
I did not have money to come home for her funeral.

203
00:07:34.701 --> 00:07:38.480
I was too embarrassed to ask anyone.

204
00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:41.080
I mean my ex-husband, many relatives,

205
00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:44.300
even my kids would have probably sent me money to come home.

206
00:07:44.300 --> 00:07:46.860
But again, my secret was just,

207
00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:50.300
it was so hard for me to tell the truth, even to myself.

208
00:07:50.300 --> 00:07:52.941
So I missed my grandmother's funeral.

209
00:07:52.941 --> 00:07:55.341
One of the things I wanted to say about that is

210
00:07:55.341 --> 00:07:57.140
you know we miss opportunities

211
00:07:57.140 --> 00:07:58.801
when we get in financial situations,

212
00:07:58.801 --> 00:08:01.840
and quite often there will be another opportunity,

213
00:08:01.840 --> 00:08:04.060
but that was a lost opportunity.

214
00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:06.620
I can never go to my grandmother's funeral.

215
00:08:06.620 --> 00:08:10.921
That's one of the real painful losses that I really regret.

216
00:08:10.921 --> 00:08:13.820
<v Regina>But this shame thing surrounds money.</v>

217
00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:15.261
If we don't handle it well,

218
00:08:15.261 --> 00:08:16.901
and this can be from someone

219
00:08:16.901 --> 00:08:18.860
making millions of dollars a year,

220
00:08:18.860 --> 00:08:22.620
to someone how has run out of their unemployment benefits.

221
00:08:22.620 --> 00:08:23.820
It doesn't really matter.

222
00:08:23.820 --> 00:08:25.381
It's not discriminating in that way

223
00:08:25.381 --> 00:08:30.280
to have a shameful, unhealthy relationship to money.

224
00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:31.200
Right?

225
00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:31.800
<v ->Right,</v>

226
00:08:31.800 --> 00:08:33.661
and I think that when we think about shame,

227
00:08:33.661 --> 00:08:35.881
there's two ways that I like to think about it.

228
00:08:35.881 --> 00:08:39.040
There's the same that comes from the situation

229
00:08:39.040 --> 00:08:40.160
that we found ourselves in.

230
00:08:40.160 --> 00:08:41.840
That we're embarrassed to tell anyone about.

231
00:08:41.840 --> 00:08:44.280
Then there's the shame that we grow up

232
00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:48.461
and we feel inside that we're not worthy.

233
00:08:48.461 --> 00:08:50.520
That there's this emptiness,

234
00:08:50.520 --> 00:08:52.800
the sense of deprivation in our lives.

235
00:08:52.800 --> 00:08:56.860
And so we feel as though there's something wrong with us.

236
00:08:56.860 --> 00:08:59.380
You know, John Bradshaw, who wrote the forward to my book

237
00:08:59.380 --> 00:09:02.680
had written the book, "Healing the Shame that Binds You."

238
00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:05.080
John Bradshaw talks about the fact

239
00:09:05.080 --> 00:09:07.740
that when we feel this shame,

240
00:09:07.740 --> 00:09:10.801
when we didn't get our needs met when we were small,

241
00:09:10.801 --> 00:09:13.260
that we almost feel that we're damaged goods.

242
00:09:13.260 --> 00:09:14.780
That there's something wrong with us,

243
00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:17.820
so we're coming from a shame based place.

244
00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:19.540
And quite often what we will do,

245
00:09:19.540 --> 00:09:21.281
we will create the outside of our life

246
00:09:21.281 --> 00:09:23.340
to match how we feel about ourselves inside.

247
00:09:23.340 --> 00:09:24.980
<v Regina>And this is very subconscious?</v>

248
00:09:24.980 --> 00:09:27.420
<v ->It's subconscious and this is the thing about</v>

249
00:09:27.420 --> 00:09:29.920
when we get into, "Okay, what do people do about it."

250
00:09:29.920 --> 00:09:32.180
We want to get conscious,

251
00:09:32.180 --> 00:09:36.500
because if we have these unconscious motivators

252
00:09:36.500 --> 00:09:38.000
driving our behaviors

253
00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.340
and we have no idea that's going on,

254
00:09:40.340 --> 00:09:42.860
and that was certainly part of the case for me.

255
00:09:42.860 --> 00:09:46.981
That it's very difficult to really change our situation.

256
00:09:46.981 --> 00:09:49.560
We wonder, "Gee, I'm smart.

257
00:09:49.560 --> 00:09:51.600
